<subSubSection pageId="64" pageNumber="65" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="64.[128,654,1290,1759]" lastBlockId="64.[701,1228,1291,1759]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
DISCUSSION: The unique color pattern distinguishes this species from all others of the genus. The reddish fuscous to black pronotum has a whitish broad band along the posterior margin. Curiously, the same distinctive color pattern is exhibited by some specimens of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Knight)" baseAuthorityName="Knight" baseAuthorityYear="1938" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Scalponotatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albibasis">
<emphasis box="[928,1227,1380,1403]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Scalponotatus albibasis</emphasis>
(Knight)
</taxonomicName>
, which occurs in southwestern 
<collectingCountry name="United States of America" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">U. S.</collectingCountry>
and northwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[974,1065,1440,1462]" name="Mexico" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. The typical 
<taxonomicName box="[701,816,1469,1492]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Jornandes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[701,816,1469,1492]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Jornandes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
type of sculpturing is easily seen, whereas 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Knight" baseAuthorityYear="1938" box="[801,930,1498,1521]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Scalponotatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albibasis">
<emphasis box="[801,817,1499,1520]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[832,930,1498,1521]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">albibasis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a roughened dorsum. All specimens were collected into alcohol at light. No setae were present on the hemelytral membrane. This is the only known species of 
<taxonomicName box="[701,816,1617,1640]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Jornandes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[701,816,1617,1640]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Jornandes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurring in 
<collectingRegion box="[985,1223,1618,1640]" country="Mexico" name="Baja California Sur" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Baja California Sur</collectingRegion>
. A female was selected as 
<typeStatus box="[1001,1103,1647,1669]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">holotype</typeStatus>
because it was better preserved than any of the three available males.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
